<subSubSection id="2CD00E865CDA43F0BF11F1C22BE8C85B" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="holotype">
<paragraph id="0C439237F6A6E57DF671D10943C618C0" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Holotype.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CEA1F3D3675193F52DF5AA675FE34535" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
Female. Plate XXXIII-2, figs 165, 166, 167 in 
<bibRefCitation id="681D4BE68F0ECA45EAC9DDF49DBD452B" author="Zhang, JF" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" refId="B147" refString="Zhang, JF, Sun, B, Zhang, XY, 1994. Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong. Science Press, Beijing" title="Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong." year="1994">Zhang et al. (1994)</bibRefCitation>
. We were not able study the holotype (see comment under 
<taxonomicName id="F44FD263374863973351C7645C5F4D7F" genus="B." lsidName="B. luianus" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="luianus">
<emphasis id="38223996F60349FE336415DF5D886A41" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">B. luianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, vide supra).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5CF6DE77D3687A03B808625F2954C9A7" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="type strata and locality">
<paragraph id="1E8F3A89B09E8461C9F30B68AA1D8EE9" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Type strata and locality.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="93A1E0F5FD34641E892A26A7B9116E3F" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Middle Miocence (i.e., 17.0-15.2 Ma), deposit of the Shanwang Formation, large lacustrine and lithified deposit, with diatomaceous and tuffaceous mudstone. Located in Linqu County, Shanwang Province, China.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="60024747110E3EB43A654BD3027BB5AF" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="description">
<paragraph id="2176E49EDCC312757DDF03EBDD29EAC9" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B640BE0B04D2967A1C0AFE741751937C" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
Taken from 
<bibRefCitation id="01FCDC1F214759A96DA9D7281E508B41" author="Zhang, JF" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" refId="B147" refString="Zhang, JF, Sun, B, Zhang, XY, 1994. Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong. Science Press, Beijing" title="Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong." year="1994">Zhang et al. (1994)</bibRefCitation>
: Forewing blackish brown, opaque; forewing and hind wing papillate distally; forewing length approximately 15.0 mm, maximum width approximately 6.00 mm as preserved; basal vein relatively straight and basad cu-a; cu-a almost straight; marginal cell length almost 5.0 mm, width 1.1 mm; 1st abscissa of Rs almost straight; 2nd abscissa of Rs slightly curved near midpoint; r-rs straight; Rs+M straight and longer than r-rs; 3Rs straight and smaller than r-rs; 4Rs straight and approximately as long as Rs+M; three submarginal cells, second smallest; 1rs-m straight; 2rs-m curved apically in its posterior half; 1m-cu relatively straight, reaching M near midpoint between 2nd abscissa of Rs and 1rs-m; 2m-cu curved apically, reaching M basad to 2rs-m; total body length approximately 13.0 mm as preserved (large part of metasoma missing). See 
<bibRefCitation id="65B2077EF3B22331A28B8D8E5E3563B9" author="Zhang, JF" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" refId="B147" refString="Zhang, JF, Sun, B, Zhang, XY, 1994. Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong. Science Press, Beijing" title="Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong." year="1994">Zhang et al. (1994)</bibRefCitation>
for original description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FE694B830D71BA33AC3AC530A24466F3" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="comments">
<paragraph id="23C0C76CD0AB85721C4B427573EF90F6" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8E46478EEE88E741D826DD49F1E13D53" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
The specimen was described as 
<taxonomicName id="64B34EF8CAC5ED77FC7ADEDFA6B57E12" genus="B." lsidName="B. anacolus" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="anacolus">
<emphasis id="03A1F9708581D5191E70501A5D2E54BF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">B. anacolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="34C0046370D533C22B1D38951DD234EB" author="Zhang, JF" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" refId="B147" refString="Zhang, JF, Sun, B, Zhang, XY, 1994. Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong. Science Press, Beijing" title="Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong." year="1994">Zhang et al. (1994)</bibRefCitation>
, and considered to be close to 
<taxonomicName id="12ECC01B300056E5735A2C2C5AA1CB99" genus="B." lsidName="B. luianus" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="luianus">
<emphasis id="ABD7C086CB5B27BACEAF4CA0E7CFB53B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">B. luianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species collected from the same deposit. Based on geometric morphometric analyses this species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="55DCC37A5A54D3A91E78508999191095" authority="Skorikov, 1914" authorityName="Skorikov" authorityYear="1914" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Mendacibombus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mendacibombus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="697915C40F674AA3374027131D9C8239" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Mendacibombus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and it could be a relative of this subgenus. This hypothesis is supported by the fact that 
<taxonomicName id="B1E1ABB56A0AC1ED858882C6474F8410" authority="Skorikov, 1914" authorityName="Skorikov" authorityYear="1914" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Mendacibombus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mendacibombus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4BA2F2FCD531DFF7FC31608382BBFC98" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Mendacibombus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is estimated to have originated around the Eocene-Oligocene boundary (i.e., 34 Ma) in the Old World (
<bibRefCitation id="EB1797DF82CC7DED033A88D83785968E" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/10635150801898912" author="Hines, HM" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="58 - 75" refId="B55" refString="Hines, HM, 2008. Historical biogeography, divergence times, and diversification patterns of bumblebees (Hymenoptera: Apidae: Bombus). Systematic Biology 57: 58 - 75" title="Historical biogeography, divergence times, and diversification patterns of bumblebees (Hymenoptera: Apidae: Bombus)." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/10635150801898912" volume="57" year="2008">Hines 2008</bibRefCitation>
), while the fossil was discovered in the Middle Lower Miocene (i.e., 17.0-15.2 Ma) deposit of Shandong in China (
<bibRefCitation id="6E5C391816DB5E75FA0F0512F2647E8C" author="Zhang, JF" journalOrPublisher="Acta Zootaxonomica Sinica" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="83 - 91" refId="B146" refString="Zhang, JF, 1990. New fossil species of Apoidea (Insecta: Hymenoptera). Acta Zootaxonomica Sinica 15: 83 - 91" title="New fossil species of Apoidea (Insecta: Hymenoptera)." volume="15" year="1990">Zhang 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="C17DBF1D1BA4E454C37A543058B3C88D" author="Zhang, JF" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" refId="B147" refString="Zhang, JF, Sun, B, Zhang, XY, 1994. Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong. Science Press, Beijing" title="Miocene Insects and Spiders from Shanwang, Shandong." year="1994">Zhang et al. 1994</bibRefCitation>
). Moreover, the crown age of extant members of 
<taxonomicName id="9A91008D176ADBBB651874B31D0B79BF" authority="Skorikov, 1914" authorityName="Skorikov" authorityYear="1914" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Mendacibombus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mendacibombus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B8C2770705D81833EF40B57F656675CE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Mendacibombus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
apparently diversified during the Late Miocene (i.e., 8 Ma). As observed for 
<taxonomicName id="804AE7479908F6528805EF2E354120AB" genus="B." lsidName="B. luianus" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="luianus">
<emphasis id="8F6199DFFD24117DAE41D8A988A29ECD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">B. luianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="11D2BB0A3CD4A045A9CF23CD1EA7EFE0" genus="B." lsidName="B. dilectus" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="dilectus">
<emphasis id="C8CA7555BC5B0CE2A7E70469C07376CA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">B. dilectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, results based on geometric morphometric analyses for this species could be wrong since it was based on 
<normalizedToken id="7880EAC8FAFAA3C2387C19063AE8E503" originalValue="Zhang’s">Zhang's</normalizedToken>
drawings. Given this, we consider the fossil as species inquirenda.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
